6","1204":"1204","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","about 1228":"about 1228","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","about 1215":"about 1215","1244":"1244","1208":"1208","Kirkham, Lancashire, England":"Kirkham, Lancashire, England","Garstang, Lancashire, England":"Garstang, Lancashire, England","Over Kellet, Lancashire, England":"Over Kellet, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Singleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and West Yorkshire):","habitational name from Singleton (Lancashire), probably from Old English <i>scingol</i> ‘shingle, wooden roof tile’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Bearers of this surname are said to be descended from Ughtred <i>de Sinleton</i>, holder of lands in Amounderness wapentake (Lancashire) <i>c.</i> 1160–90. This name was first recorded in Ireland in 1308 and firmly established in Louth and Monaghan during the 17th century.","habitational name from Singleton (Sussex), probably from Old English <i>sængel</i>, <i>sengel</i> ‘bundle, tuft’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Singelton","meanings":["English: variant of   Singleton  ."]},{"name":"Shingleton","meanings":["English: late medieval variant of   Singleton  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":7,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":16,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilda de Singleton was born in 1208, in Kirkham, Lancashire, England, her father, Alan de Singleton, was 11205 and her mother, Alice Winwick, was 17. She had at least 2 daughters with Adam de Kellet. She died in 1258, in Garstang, Lancashire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1208–1258":"1208–1258","1204–1262":"1204–1262","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1226–M